EXAMPLE DATA

This assignment contains many code demonstrations which use a subsetted version of the iris dataset. This subsetted version contains only NINE TOTAL ROWS, with three rows for each species. The code below shows how it was created as well as what it looks like:

iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  # Add 1-50 for each species - you'll want to run this yourself to see! n() is a useful dplyr function itself that you'll learn about in this HW
  mutate(row_number = 1:n()) %>%
  # Only keep the first 3 observations per group
  filter(row_number <= 3) %>%
  # We're done with row_number, get rid of it
  select(-row_number) %>%
  # ungroup or else species grouping will remain!
  ungroup() -> iris9

1.4. You’ll notice in the last question, the plant_growth.csv dataset has a column called plant_id. This column uniquely identifies each plant so that after we pivot, we can clearly tell which plant is which. To see how important this is, again use pivot_wider() on this dataset in the same way as the last question, but this time first select OUT the plant_id column (select(-plant_id)).

You will the output is very funky with a LOT of warnings. This main warning message describes the problem: “Values are not uniquely identified; output will contain list-cols.” Indeed, rows are NOT uniquely identified.



1.5. Let’s now learn how to solve this problem - what if we had a dataset that did not already contain a column to uniquely identify each plant or participant? We would have to make one before pivoting. The best way to accomplish this is to use mutate to create a column that contains a unique number. dplyr has a helper function n() which will provide the total number of observations in a group - if the data is ungrouped, it’s just the full number of rows. Run the example below to understand how n() works.

iris9 %>%
  # Create a column `row_number` with values 1-9 (iris9 has 9 rows only)
  mutate(row_number = 1:n()) ## 1:n() makes an array, 1 - number of rows.

Part 2: Practicing tidy-select magic

When pivoting, we often need to provide a bunch of columns. It is often easier to list these columns some select() magic. We have previously seen the magic of everything() (select everything else!). This magic actually comes to us from tidy-select, functionality in dplyr for cleanly specifying a set of columns.

You need to use our old standard coffee_ratings dataset for this part of the HW. Link to coffee.

For this set of questions, you will teach yourself some more magic by following examples and applying the concept to a new scenario. All examples use the subsetted iris9 dataset created for these demos.

3.2. For this question, we will learn how to make a line plot, which is a great way to visualize data over time. Line plots are made with geom_line() and require an aes called group which should map to the variable that indicates how points should be connected.

Again using the life expectancy dataset in a single connected pipeline, pivot to a full tidy dataframe, choose TWO countries over a 10 YEAR PERIOD, and plot their life expectancies over time as a line plot. Guidelines:

  • Make sure the countries are distinguished by color, and also remember to NOT use the default color scheme.
  • In this case, each line represents values for a single country. This means that country should be mapped to group. If you don’t use this aesthetic, the plot will not work properly.
  • You may also want to use geom_point() in addition to geom_line() so that you can more clearly see the values at each year. Up to you!!
